@node Match actions
@section Match actions

@findex isearch-extras-exit-other-end
@findex isearch-extras-copy-match
@findex isearch-extras-yank-kill-literally
Three commands provide additional actions you can take on the current isearch match:

@itemize
@item
@code{isearch-extras-exit-other-end} exits the search and moves point to the opposite end of the match. Normally, isearch leaves point at the end of the match when searching forward, or at the beginning when searching backward. This command inverts that behavior, which is useful when you want to edit the text just before a match found by a forward search.

@item
@code{isearch-extras-copy-match} copies the text of the current match to the kill ring and exits the search. The copied region spans from point to @code{isearch-other-end}, so it captures exactly the matched text. This is convenient when you want to use the match as a template for replacement or insertion elsewhere.

@item
@code{isearch-extras-yank-kill-literally} inserts the most recent kill ring entry into the isearch prompt as literal text, without interpreting regexp metacharacters. The standard isearch yank commands may treat the yanked text as a pattern; this command avoids that by processing each character through @code{isearch-text-char-description}.
@end itemize

@node Search escalation
@section Search escalation

@findex isearch-extras-consult-line
@findex isearch-extras-project-search
Two commands let you seamlessly escalate an in-buffer isearch to a broader search scope:

@itemize
@item
@code{isearch-extras-consult-line} transfers the current search string to @code{consult-line} from the @samp{consult} package. It saves the search string to the isearch ring, exits the isearch session, and immediately starts @code{consult-line} with the same query (regexp-quoted if the search was not already in regexp mode). This is useful when you realize mid-search that you want to see all matches at once with preview.

@item
@code{isearch-extras-project-search} transfers the current search string to @code{project-find-regexp}. Like @code{isearch-extras-consult-line}, it saves the string, exits isearch, and immediately starts a project-wide search. This lets you escalate from ``searching in this buffer'' to ``searching in all project files'' without retyping the query.
@end itemize

Both commands preserve the isearch ring so the query remains available for future searches.

